Yesterday I posted a screenshot of messages that I had recieved from a man I don't know. He told me that he was sexually aroused whaching my character on a tv show being held as a hostage and tied up. I posted also my thoughts: "I'm sick of these type of messages. Seriously why would you send these type of messages to a person who doesn't even know you? It just makes her feel very uncomfortable." That wasn't an unusual text. I get plenty of DMs and comments from strange men telling me about their sexual response of seeing my pictures, characters I've played or even hearing my voice. I can say that I have already grown a thick skin throughout the years but still I know what is right and what's wrong. I recieved my first dickpic when I was 16. Now I'm 22 and still I get harrased on internet. What have I done to stop them texting me before? I have ignored, blocked and reported them. Still I get at least 3 harrasing texts per day from new men.

I got a lot of response yesterday. Many girls told me they get same type of DMs and how horrible it makes them feel. Women told me they were proud of me for what I did. Guys told me that it's awful that I had to deal with that type of things. Most of them told me just to ignore that type of creeps or that I should grow a thicker skin. Some told me it was the price of fame.

My response to that was: "No, it's the price of being born female." They told me that they were sorry to hear that. 
Sexual harrasment is NEVER okay. It should not be ignored. Showing people that you have been treated badly is not something you should be shamed of. This is not about being weak. This is power of #metoo.

Be brave everyone!

On 28th February, a group of 30 Bangaloreans gathered at our courtyard to discuss the Art vs Artist issue, in light of #MeToo. 
As a cultural venue, we have been pondering over how to look at the issue, whether to dismiss art created by artists accused of misdeeds, or view an artwork as having its own life, independent of the creator.

In a most engaging discussion moderated by Pavithra Sankaran, we managed to touch upon various aspects of the problem by creating a safe space for conversation. From the role of the individual vs collective opinion, to the role of social media in today’s outrage culture, to the sharing of experiences and thoughts on the matter, it was a wholesome discussion that brought up and addressed some essential questions, as well as threw light on the grey areas.

Having said that, it was not easy to come to one conclusion or solution given the vastness of the topic. Here are a few thought-provoking questions that came up which we’d like to leave you to think about: -What are the implications of separating an artwork from the artist? -In the #MeToo era, do artworks made my wrongdoers deserve a place in museums and galleries? -By appreciating or looking at a work made by a known miscreant, are you enabling the perpetrator? -Is boycotting and public shaming the only way to tackle this issue? Or are there more humane solutions like reforms? -Finally, what is your take on the issue?

You can share your thoughts in the Comments section or email us atinfo@thecourtyardcommunity.in. We hope to have many more such open discussions in the near future.

Word for Saturday🙏
。
How are you breaking your patterns?
。
From my personal experience I would advise you to take it easy, start VERY SLOWLY.
。
I am a ‘maximizer’, which means I go either 0 or 100⚡️
If I do something I’m passionate about I am 100% there.
。
This is what I felt towards plastic surgery and microsurgery.
When I was operating under a microscope during a course at @lmu.muenchen time was flying.
The surgeon leading the course named my anastamosis (connection between two vessels) the best of the course.
I was just after my internship in Poland and in the room there were 20 adult doctors, most of them specialists in field of plastic surgery and hand surgery.
。
Many plastic surgeons during my internships all around the world were telling me that I have an outstanding talent.
。
But when I started working at the Trauma Surgery Unit of the University Clinic in Innsbruck something changed in me forever.
I was mobbed by my work colleague.
。
I was told every day by a man higher in the clinic’s hierarchy than me, that I am worthless.
Every day for 3 months.
This influenced my entire life.
。
I stopped believing in myself.
My dreams of becoming a plastic and reconstructive surgeon making face transplantations got ruined.
I had to run away.
I quit my job.
People were coming to me and saying:
‘I hope you don’t quit because of HIM, EVERYONE knows, that he is a chauvinist’
。
EVERYONE knew.
And NO ONE reacted.
I quit my job because of HIM.
Take it or leave it.
This is the truth.
。
I’m unemployed now.
I get the money from the state of Austria to go to psychotherapy.
My family is ashamed of me, because I failed at being a Doctor.
。
But I won’t give up.
I am going to heal.
I am going to work as a Doctor again.
I am going to help make this world a better place.
I just need time to break the negative patterns this man imprinted in my brain.
I am going to be a great Doctor.
I just need to survive this storm ⛈ 
Keep your fingers crossed guys.
And if you pray, pray for me🙏
Once I’m good again I’m going to give back to you♥️
。
。
。

I will always and forever be proud to be a woman. I was taught since I was little “don’t be too loud”, “don’t talk too much”, “don’t wear this”, “this isn’t ladylike”. These type of comments have made me a very insecure and a confused teenage girl that had to go against what my natural instincts have told me to do. I didn’t know what to do in life, how to act around boys, how to express myself without being judged for who I am. 
It is extremely challenging to live in a world that is still run by those principles. 
If you are a young girl, please don’t be afraid to speak up. Nobody should be bringing you down if your heart and intentions are pure. I have been held back in life by men (and some women) that have shamed me into thinking that I was never enough, imperfect, loud, nosy, obnoxious, know it all, naive etc. Bottom line is, be yourself, live for yourself. Stay kind and pure and the universe will take care of the rest 💗

San Francisco Giants team president and CEO Larry Baer apologized Friday night after video earlier in the day showed him having an altercation with his wife during a fight over his cellphone at a San Francisco park.
The incident was caught on video and published on TMZ Sports.
In the video, Baer's wife, Pam, screams, "Oh, my God! No!" while falling to the ground as her husband attempts to take the cellphone from her. The video also shows Larry Baer holding that cellphone while walking away.
In a statement Friday night, Pam Baer attempted to clarify what occurred. She said she took her husband's cellphone and did not want to give it back. When she attempted to get up from the chair in which she was sitting, she said it tipped and a previous foot injury caused her to lose her balance.
"I did not sustain any injury based on what happened today," she said. "Larry and I always have been and still are happily married."
The couple previously expressed regret for what happened, saying in a joint statement that they are "deeply embarrassed by the situation and have resolved the issue.''

Spotted in Berlin. 
Are you serious, Fun Factory? Referring to female hysteria and suggesting that a vibrator would be the perfect means to keep women from making trouble? Because this is what the history of female hysteria is about: First, the uterus was believed to wander around the body like an animal, hungry for semen – and only marriage, intercourse, and pregnancy was the ultimate treatment for this. The general belief was that “the uterus was a troublemaker and was best sated when pregnant”, as Terri Kapsalis explains (https://lithub.com/hysteria-witches-and-the-wandering-uterus-a-brief-history/). Later it was believed that hysteria could be caused by various bad habits like reading novels, masturbation, and homosexuality resulting in symptoms such as irrationality and general troublemaking. “It is no accident that such a diagnosis took off just as some of these same women were fighting to gain access to universities and various professions in the US and Europe”, says Kapsalis. Either Fun Factory has no clue about the scope of this history, or, which is more likely, they very well know and want to make a tongue-in-cheek joke – which is even worse. #shop #display #femalehysteria #sexistdesign #feminism #troublemaking

There can be alot of confusion on the journey of spiritual awakening. I have experienced much of it. These days, I feel so much clearer than I ever have before. Within myself and my life. I have learnt inner discernment and it came about through some unfortunate circumstances in my life. When I trusted too quickly and let my guard down. There were many experiences where I have been taken advantage of and many "leaders" and "shamans/gurus" attempted to destroy my light... I could easily name a few in the spiritual community that would destroy their reputation... Ones that live in the Byron Bay community.. And that doesn't feel in integrity with me. I told who I needed to for protection and to protect others so they don't have to go through what I went through. I have experienced physical, sexual, emotional, mental, spiritual abuse. From many different beings from many different circumstances. I don't wish this upon anyone. Yet so many go through this too. Even though it was deeply traumatising, many many gifts have come from them. If you have been through abuse, do not spiritually bypass and ignore it. You deserve a safe and sacred space to be heard, to be felt, to be loved for what you went through. It's not your fault, but it is your responsibility to heal. You don't have to suffer beloved. It's time to speak up, tell your story. Write it out, cry it out, dance it out.. Seek professional help. Invest in yourself.. I am hesitant sharing this because its incredibly vulnerable.. Yet its important.. I have the privilege of using my voice and I will not take it for granted. With love, Abby x

Wylie said that Bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when Cambridge Analytica consulted various Republican campaigns and PACs ahead of the midterm elections. The company began to test and apply its psychographics by using Facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

Documents show the John Bolton Super PAC, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed White House national security adviser John Bolton, paid Cambridge Analytica $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." Those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

Wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the Trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "A lot of the narratives of the Trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," Wylie said.

He added that Bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "Everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to Bannon for approval," said Wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

Wylie said Bannon would fly to London about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand Bannon's ideology. "He really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," Wylie said.

Curt Devine, Donie O'Sullivan & Drew Griffin
CNN

But Wylie wasn’t just talking about fashion. He had recently been exposed to a new discipline: “information operations”, which ranks alongside land, sea, air and space in the US military’s doctrine of the “five-dimensional battle space”. His brief ranged across the SCL Group – the British government has paid SCL to conduct counter-extremism operations in the Middle East, and the US Department of Defense has contracted it to work in Afghanistan.

I tell him that another former employee described the firm as “MI6 for hire”, and I’d never quite understood it.
.
- It’s like dirty MI6 because you’re not constrained. There’s no having to go to a judge to apply for permission. It’s normal for a ‘market research company’ to amass data on domestic populations. And if you’re working in some country and there’s an auxiliary benefit to a current client with aligned interests, well that’s just a bonus.
.
When I ask how Bannon even found SCL, Wylie tells me what sounds like a tall tale, though it’s one he can back up with an email about how Mark Block, a veteran Republican strategist, happened to sit next to a cyberwarfare expert for the US air force on a plane. - And the cyberwarfare guy is like, ‘Oh, you should meet SCL. They do cyberwarfare for elections.’
.
It was Bannon who took this idea to the Mercers: Robert Mercer – the co-CEO of the hedge fund Renaissance Technologies, who used his billions to pursue a rightwing agenda, donating to Republican causes and supporting Republican candidates – and his daughter Rebekah.

Carole Cadwalladr
The Guardian

According to the Times, Cambridge Analytica bought the data from Aleksandr Kogan, a Russian-American academic. Kogan, who told Facebook he was conducting academic research, built a Facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." When users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available Facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

More than a quarter-million Facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a Facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. By prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, Kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

Throughout 2015 and into 2016, the Cruz campaign paid Cambridge Analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like Iowa and New Hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. Using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer".
.
In December 2015, the same month The Guardian revealed Cambridge Analytica and Kogan's data harvesting practices, Cruz campaign spokesman Rick Tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field."
.
Despite Tyler's claim that the Cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying Cambridge Analytica until June of that year, a month after Cruz suspended his campaign. After Cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with Trump, supporting him through November's general election against Hillary Clinton.

Stephen Young
Dallas Observer

On My First Love:

Hold still. This might hurt a little. This is love. This is the tide turning, skull burning intergalactic love you read about as a child. The love of Heathcliff and Catherine running in the moors. The love of Alice and her Mad hatter. The love you imagined with barbie and ken in hand. Hold still. This might sting a little. Like a bees last defiant act of self love. You will do the same for him, you will lose your stinger, lose your heart, lose your mind, to keep him from harm. Hold still. For holding still is the only way to catch it all, that crooked smile of his, the urgent kisses, the sleepy morning talks. This is the ‘top of the ferris wheel’ kind of love, the ‘lets jump in that puddle’ kind of love, this is the passionate screaming, midnight loving kind of love. Hold still. Don’t run, don’t hide, it will find you either way my darling. Hold still. Let it get you. Let it overwhelm you. Let yourself fall hard, into the rabbit hole. It will pick you up, it will heal you, it will keep you safe. Hold still. This is love.

This time last year I marched with some of my nearest and dearest in the 40th anniversary of Mardi Gras. This year I find myself in the US missing my friends and family, but living a very lucky life to say the least. 
Mardi Gras for me represents a celebration of all things diverse and I know there are people that have fought long and hard for that privilege and will continue to do so. To those I am thankful and eternally grateful.

I’m fortunate to be part of the rainbow community and I acknowledge there are other communities and groups that suffer under similar circumstances. The fight is not over.

I know I live in a bubble of support from friends and family that others are not so fortunate to have. To all of you I thank and love you and know you are loved.

I say to the bigots and ignorant people of this world. Grow the fuck up! 
Be the change and accept people for who they are for the world will be a better place. I need not mention the naysayers who are now convicted of crimes beyond belief.

To those that feel alone and isolated, know that it does get better. There are people that love you and will support you. You are not alone. Find your family.

We have the great pleasure this year to welcome Blo Vancouver owner Jenny Randhawa to our program this year - this has been in the works for a long time, and we're so glad to pass you the mic! .
.
Jenny graduated with a Master's in Health Administration from UBC in 2005. With eight years of management consulting experience, a strong background of education and practical experience, it’s no wonder that she has become a force to be reckoned with in the business world. In 2007 Jenny decided to tackle new territory — the beauty industry. When Blo Blow Dry Bar launched in 2007, Jenny was the first to be considered for a franchise partnership and has been with the company since day one, savouring the successes and learning and perfecting the ropes. Following the success of her first bar in early 2010, Jenny acquired all 3 of Vancouver’s Blo bars six months later as well as the rights to all of British Columbia, striking while the (curling) iron was hot! Since then, Jenny continues to lead this multi-unit company demonstrating her strengths in all aspects of business management including operations, efficency, growth strategy, conflict resolution, brand and culture management, organizational structure as well as strategic planning. In 2019, Blo Corporate recognized her as a leading Franchise Partner out of 130+ Blo locations in Social Media Management, Staff Management, Retention and Culture and Outstanding Contributor to Operational Growth Strategies. Her greatest passion is to provide one-on-one support and guidance to her fellow entrepreneurs.

A 17 years old teenage girl from northwestern China has created shock waves by publicly accusing a schoolteacher of four years of rape, physical abuse and blackmail.

The girl, now 17, told the City and Youth Channel of Shaanxi Television on Wednesday that the teacher at Chenggu County No 4 Middle School in Shaanxi province forced her into a sexual relationship and threatened her with violence if she spoke about the attacks. "All girls who have come forward in an environment with such a patchy rule of law and pressure from the public are brave," another said.

Students at schools and colleges began to speak out last year in the wake of the international #MeToo movement and a national campaign against sexual harassment that spread across schools and college campuses.

A year ago, Luo Qianqian, a former student at Beihang University in Beijing, alleged that she and at least five other women had been sexually harassed by one of their professors. The professor was fired after an inquiry found his behaviour "was a breach of administrative discipline and the norms of being a teacher". #saynotoviolence#nomore#news#China#Asia

this scene was so incredibly powerful. the way that this amazing show handles these topics with delicacy and grace completely blows me away. this episode had the perfect balance of comedy and coverage,, coverage being on a topic that is so important. the storyline in the episode was so important to be seen on tv and to have seen it was so astounding. it was completely breathtaking in every possible way and for every possible reason. the way that each scene was constructed to create this incredible storyline that illustrated so many different things: jake being an incredible ally (in this scene and many others), this conversation/debate between rosa and amy, the entire storyline and all of the issues it brought up about the world we live in: two steps forward one step back. the talent shown from all of the actors was awe-inspiring and sensational, @melissafumero ‘s acting in this scene had me speechless and teary. i am so proud of @stephaniebeatriz for having her directorial debut be on something so gravitational and powerful and she has absolutely done the #metoo movement proud. i love this show with my whole heart and this episode encapsulates so many reasons why. and to nbc for airing an episode about this topic: thank you thank you thank you!!!!!

My favorite time of the day. Sitting down and asking my heart what I need. What oils call out to me? This bag goes everywhere with me. And as I mentioned in a previous post from today, it has about 18 roller blends — roller tops on my faves, or blends I created myself.
⠀⠀
Tonight, these three call to me. Sacred Mountain, Release and a blend I call Self Love (Acceptance, Abundance & Joy) ✨💓🌸 Release and I have a wonderful, thriving relationship. Last summer I remember watching a movie with my partner Travis and one of our friends. And it reminded me of the toxic relationship I ran away from a few months ago. The manipulation, the blame, shame and abuse.
⠀⠀
Release was created for exactly that purpose. To let go of anger and trauma, deep emotions that are housed in the memory center of the liver. Did you know that our body hangs into trauma at a cellular level?! Our body hangs onto memories far longer than our mind!
⠀⠀
I roll Release over my liver (underneath the right breast) to help support my emotions. The forgiveness I’ve been able to give to others and to myself — I NEVER would have thought I could get to this point of healing. And a lot of that process has to do with oils to help support.
⠀⠀
Oils don’t heal or cure anything, babes. They are plant juices that touch our bodies in such an intimate and personal way. But they sure as GOODNESS make like a whole lot easier and lovely ✨🌸💛
⠀⠀
This was a liiiiiittle more deep, but authenticity is what I’m about. If we’re gonna lift each other up, it’s gotta be in the serious stuff, too. You are always welcome on my little corner of Instagram — @bethany_bourgoin & @vibrantheartessentials. Because you are so stinkin’ worthy, girl 💓🌻
⠀⠀

Kaki saya yang pendek seringkali menyulitkan saya menjangkau tempat-tempat yang saya inginkan. Mau nonton pawai, mau nonton konser, mau lihat artis lewat di tengah kerumunan, harus jinjit. Itu pun belum tentu sukses.
.
Tapi kaki saya yang pendek ini sering mengingatkan saya akan keterbatasan saya dan betapa saya ini bukan apa-apa tanpa mereka-mereka yang berada di sekitar saya untuk membantu saya.
.
Dan kalau “A Story of Wounds” (jangan bosen-bosen denger ini di temlen saya ya, netijen) bakal sampai Jogja di akhir bulan Maret ini, sudah jelas karena banyak sekali dukungan dari orang-orang di sekitar kami. Mereka yang kelihatan maupun yang enggak kelihatan. Mereka adalah orang-orang yang membantu kaki-kaki pendek seperti kaki saya ini untuk melangkah maju dan naik ke tempat yang lebih tinggi. Seperti kawan saya @puspitadesi_ yang bisa-bisa aja ambil foto yang sedang ‘krengkangan’ ini dengan apik.
.
Sulit bukan berarti tidak bisa. Tetap doakan dan dukung kami, kawan-kawan, karena tanpa kalian, kaki-kaki pendek ini tidak akan berjalan lebih jauh dan tidak akan melompat lebih tinggi.
.

The PROS of this is include that now that we are considered employees, we can STRIKE and UNIONIZE to create better working conditions for ourselves because we don’t have a choice. We’re employees now. We have dealt with sexual harassment from management & other non-dancing club workers, racism, homophobia, ageism & ableism for far too long. This is LITERALLY our time to strike and band together to help each other. Also, founders of the #MeToo movement are backing the founders of @soldiers.of.pole who are lawyered up and ready to go to start this industry change for the better. That should tell you something. The dispensable child - I'm the dispensable child, the unwanted, the ugly, the stupid, the incompetent, the unworthy... They wished I was never born. "It could've been better, if he was aborted" they said. "He's a burden and he brings us shame", they said. Those words pierced my heart, apart from the violence and insults I had to bear, pain a child should never endure. Then came my sibling. Someone younger, smarter, fairer. Someone they wanted, someone who was competent and someone who was worthy. I slowly pushed away, neglected and the monsters where there all the time, lurking and watching. Soon, the chance presented itself, for the monsters to exploit me and abuse me, because I'm the dispensable child.

Struggle to achieve - 
As Queer POC, it's not easy to achieve our goals and our dreams in a world dominated by archaic and toxic white patriarchy and it's colonial stain. We are forced to battle visible and invisible demons on our path to achievement. Our existence irks the privileged as they're used to seeing us as only victims and pile of bodies. We've to struggle and go that extra mile just to be on par with the majority. We have problems which have weaved through and around us. Most of us are born with depression and PTSD or acquire them through the hellish lives we live. Then, there're venomous problems which slowly slither over us and put us in a chokehold. We give up, fall and some of us perish. But, there're some of us, who're fighters. Who don't give up, who support one another and challenge evil and unjust authorities. Everyday we bathe in self confidence and tell ourselves we're worthy and tell others like us that they're worthy. We charge ahead, in spite of the judgmental glare, in spite of the vapid mockery and in spite of the unrequited violence. We move up and forward. Because, to live is to battle, to succeed is to struggle and to exist is to survive.

Yesterday, on February 28th, the Homewood Academic Council decided to revoke Professor Juan Obarrio’s tenure and terminate his employment with Johns Hopkins University. 
Anyone acquainted with American academia knows how historic this decision is. For far too long, we have seen survivors of sexual violence on and off campuses see their attackers remain in positions of power, maintain their credibility and continue to prey upon vulnerable people. But that just changed. The Academic Council, with pressure from every single one of you who held them accountable, just set a precedent that can provide hope for survivors everywhere. 
There is still a long way for Johns Hopkins to go. Many of the demands from our petition are yet to be met. We know that sexual violence on this campus is systemic, institutionalized, covered up and ignored. We know the university needs to change its procedures of investigation, drastically and as soon as possible. We know it has made mistakes that simply cannot be reversed. But this is a momentous and encouraging first step. The JHToo movement teaches us that collective action, breaking institutional silence, intersectional solidarity, and the care of our peers can indeed change things for the better. 
With your participation in our protest, our petition, our letter-writing campaign and our social media outreach, we  collectively made the seemingly impossible, possible. 
The Academic Council’s decision needs to be approved by the Provost, the President and the Board of Trustees. Professor Obarrio can still appeal this decision. We are watching all these stakeholders, to make sure that this process reaches its just conclusion. We really are almost there. Once it does reach its conclusion, this will be the first time in the history of JHU’s Homewood campus that a professor’s tenure is revoked. 
For everyone still fighting out there - we will and we must keep fighting together. It hasn’t been easy, and every step of the way we faced people who dissuaded us from speaking out and demoralized us. But more importantly, we kept going because of the people who did believe in us. Thank you to our countless supporters and fellow activists.

How shame works ..... The saying “misery loves company” is so true when it comes to sexual abuse and the minds of those who abuse. Light will always attract darkness and the light of young children is precisely what is so attractive to those who abuse; the innocence, the vulnerability and the beauty and simplicity of how children see the world.  This light of young children, which I believe is the light of their soul, is exactly what is fractured when sexual abuse occurs.  The child is drawn into a very dark world and made to feel as though they too, are part of that world. That somehow, this darkness is part of them. It is this darkness, where the feeling of shame associated with sexual abuse originates.  However, this darkness does not belong to the child, rather it is the world of the abuser.  For those who struggle with shame associated with abuse, please remember this. It is not your darkness, it does not belong to you, it was something you were introduced to.  Nothing gets healed in the dark.  Nothing.  Remember your light. ❤️⭐️♥️ #sexualabuse #metoo #metoomovement #shame #healing #divinefeminine #divinemasculine #divine #childadvocate #parenting #educatingkids #soul

“The Feminist Five are Li Maizi (Li Tingting), Wei Tingting, Zheng Churan, Wu Rongrong, and Wang Man, a group of women’s rights activist that rose to international prominence in 2015 after being criminally detained for planning a public sexual harassment awareness campaign. […] The five remained in detention for 37 days, and were released on bail on April 13, two days after U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry issued a call for their freedom. They were released under qǔbǎo hòushěn (取保候审), meaning that they would be subject to intense surveillance, restrictions, and further investigation for up to one year.” ___

Under Chinese government’s restriction of internet and activist freedom, The Feminist Five are perceived as radical in their attempts to bring attention to sexual harassment and the #MeToo movement, a hashtag that is consistently censored. The Feminist Five and other grassroots activists skirts mass censorship by utilizing the words #RiceBunny” (#米兔 or #🍚🐰), pronounced as “mi tu”. In a world where feminism is viewed through a Western lens, it is imperative to give voices and praises to those participating in activism under regimes and rulings that deny freedom of political dissent and oppress and marginalize women and LGBTQ+ communities.

The initial paragraph was retrieved from a People of the Week article for China Digital Times, a news site that reports on “news items which are blocked, deleted or suppressed by China's state censors.” (Wiki) The image used of The Feminist Five was retrieved from a CNN article, “Fighting for their rights landed these young Chinese feminists in jail.” Li Maizi’s quote was retrieved from her Guardian op-ed article, “I went to jail for handing out stickers in China.”

[…] The five remained in detention for 37 days, and were released on bail on April 13, two days after U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry issued a call for their freedom. They were released under qǔbǎo hòushěn (取保候审), meaning that they would be subject to intense surveillance, restrictions, and further investigation for up to one year.”__

Under Chinese government’s restriction of internet and activist freedom, The Feminist Five are perceived as radical in their attempts to bring attention to sexual harassment and the #MeToo movement, a hashtag that is consistently censored. The Feminist Five and other grassroots activists skirts mass censorship by utilizing the words #RiceBunny” (#米兔 or #🍚🐰), pronounced as “mi tu”. In a world where feminism is viewed through a Western lens, it is imperative to give voices and praises to those participating in activism under regimes and rulings that deny freedom of political dissent; that oppress and marginalize women and LGBTQ+ communities.

The initial paragraph was retrieved from a People of the Week article for China Digital Times, a news site that reports on “news items which are blocked, deleted or suppressed by China's state censors.” (Wiki) The image used of The Feminist Five was retrieved from a CNN article, “Fighting for their rights landed these young Chinese feminists in jail.” Li Maizi’s quote was retrieved from her Guardian op-ed article, “I went to jail for handing out stickers in China.”

This morning as I was curling my hair a swift of sadness came over my heart. I cried and cried. You know why? I cried for the countless of women who are alone in their comfort zone. I crawled out of my comfort zone by coming back to Michigan! 😳

I'm talking to the women and girls that are alone out of survival. Afraid of being hurt. Afraid of being abused. Afraid of their Divine purpose. Its worst to be surrounded by people and still feel alone. Don't get me wrong there are women that need to be alone for real for real.  Women who have healed can stand alone in the dark never pour from a empty cup. 💕

Meaning I dont believe giving advice that I have not practiced daily mentally and emotionally.🙏 I've earned the heart to speak my truth as I know it. Humbly I went somewhere and got my inner life together.  I feel for every single mother and their daughters who are fighting life alone.

No woman should die alone.
No woman should suffer in depression alone.

You are Divine love made by God.
If you didnt know that well...now you know!

Ps...you are not alone.

It’s a simple question but a hard one to answer - and not many brands can tell you. But since Fashion Revolution started five years ago, more and more brands are publishing information about where their clothes are made. There’s still a long way to go, so join our collective voice during FASHION REVOLUTION WEEK April 23-29th to ask for change. This will be the month of our new product launch and we can’t wait to show our labels! We feature new tees offered in our Freedom Box 📦. All are made by hand and signed by their maker. We think that’s something to celebrate! You will also find handwoven accessories and of course our new leather bags! ⠀
⠀
Every garment and artisan worker who makes our accessories, bags and tees are loved, seen, heard, paid properly and working in safe conditions. Learn more in April - we hope you stop back. ⠀

To kickoff Womxn’s Herstory Month we’re excited to announce the first @this_is_jane_doc storytellers series! Featuring 5 womxn from diverse backgrounds, each with an equally courageous story to tell, #thisisjane is bound to be an insightful journey into the lives of everyday #womxn negotiating an array of trauma(s) with the help of plant medicine. ⠀
⠀
What took place at the first event speaks to the power in unapologetic womxn facing extreme circumstances with our dear friend, Jane. ⠀
⠀
Our Why: ⠀
The silence surrounding violence against womxn needs to end. We believe that cannabis is both a bridge and a vessel in ending that silence. She helps the sexual-assault survivor find her words. She helps the little girl who lost her mom at 10, negotiate a lonely and obsessive world in her thirties. She helped the violent crime survivor leave her house again. ⠀
⠀
So we tell our stories not only in homage to our personal & collective healing via plant medicine, BUT also to end the stigma against discussing the horrific things that happen to womxn all over this world every single day. ⠀
⠀
Everyday for the next 2 weeks we will be posting a different Jane’s story of trauma, healing, and ultimately, resilience. ⠀
⠀
⠀
-stay tuned + follow along at ▶️ @this_is_jane_doc ⠀
